'''Rancho La Brea''' was a {{convert|4439|acre|km2|sing=on}} [[Ranchos of California|Mexican land grant]] in present-day [[Los Angeles County, California]] given in 1828 to Antonio Jose Rocha and Nemisio Dominguez by [[José Antonio Carrillo]], the [[List of pre-statehood mayors of Los Angeles, California|Alcalde of Los Angeles]]. Rancho La Brea consisted of one square league of land of what is now [[Miracle Mile, Los Angeles, California|Wilshire's Miracle Mile]], [[Hollywood, California|Hollywood]], and parts of [[West Hollywood, California|West Hollywood]].<ref>[http://content.cdlib.org/ark:/13030/hb4c6005p3/?&brand=oac Diseño del Rancho La Brea]</ref><ref>[http://www.reisvalleyandmudville.com/images/toposantamonicasouth.jpg 1900 USGS topographic map]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>[http://digarc.usc.edu/assetserver/controller/view/search/CHS-13060 Map of old Spanish and Mexican ranchos in Los Angeles County]</ref> The grant included the famous [[La Brea Tar Pits]].<ref name="ReferenceA">{{gnis|id = 244384|name = Rancho La Brea}}</ref>
==History== The title awarded by the Alcalde in 1828 was confirmed by [[José María de Echeandía]], Governor of [[Alta California]]; in 1840, it was reconfirmed by Governor [[Juan Bautista Alvarado|Juan Alvarado]].<ref>Ogden Hoffman, 1862, ''Reports of Land Cases Determined in the United States District Court for the Northern District of California'', Numa Hubert, San Francisco</ref>
With the [[Mexican Cession|cession]] of California to the United States after the [[Mexican–American War]], the 1848 [[Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo]] provided that the land grants would be honored. As required by the [[Land Act of 1851]], a claim was filed by Antonio José Rocha, José Jorge Rocha, and Josefa de la Merced de Jordan with the [[Public Land Commission]] in 1852, but was rejected in 1860.<ref>[http://content.cdlib.org/view?docId=hb109nb422&chunk.id=c01-1.3.6.4&brand=oac United States. District Court (California : Southern District) Land Case 287 SD]</ref> As a lawyer and surveyor, [[Henry Hancock]] worked for the Rocha family to aid them with their efforts to prove their claim to Rancho La Brea. The Rochas finally won their claim (the grant was recorded as patented to "A. J. Rocha et al." in 1873).<ref>[http://www.slc.ca.gov/Misc_Pages/Historical/Surveyors_General/reports/Willey_1884_1886.pdf Report of the Surveyor General 1844 - 1886] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130320000647/http://www.slc.ca.gov/Misc_Pages/Historical/Surveyors_General/reports/Willey_1884_1886.pdf |date=March 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>[http://thelandpatents.com/patents/cacaaa-085077 Record of patent CACAAA 085077]</ref> The grant included the famous [[La Brea Tar Pits]].<ref name="ReferenceA" />
As happened to other rancheros, the claimants' legal expenses left them broke. In 1860, Antonio José Rocha's son, [[José Jorge Rocha]], deeded Rancho La Brea to [[Henry Hancock]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.laokay.com/halac/RanchoLaBrea.htm |title=Rancho La Brea |accessdate=June 19, 2010 |quote=On January 6, 1828 Rancho La Brea was granted to Antonio Jose Rocha and Nemisio Dominguez by Jose Antonio Carrillo, the Alcalde of Los Angeles. The grant included a stipulation that the tar pits within the rancho would be open and available to all the citizens of the pueblo for their use. The title was confirmed by Jose Echeandia, who was the Governor of Alta California at the time. Later in 1840, it was reconfirmed by Governor Juan B. Alvarado |publisher=LA Okay}}</ref><ref>Seaman, Florence Josephine (1914) ''A Brief History of Rancho La Brea'', Historical Society of Southern California, Vol IX, pp 253-256</ref> Hancock paid $20,000 for the Mexican grants (at $2 or $3 per acre) with his profits from the sale of gold he had found in a rich placer mine.<ref name="guinn1915">{{cite book|title=A history of California and an extended history of Los Angeles and environs, Volume 2|year=1915|publisher=Historic Record Co.|author=James Miller Guinn|page=98}}[https://books.google.com/books?id=FBYVAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA98]</ref> He engaged in the commercial development of the tar deposits on Rancho La Brea. He shipped considerable quantities to San Francisco by schooner. Most of Rancho La Brea was later subdivided and developed by his surviving son, Captain [[George Allan Hancock]].<ref>[http://www.wshphs.org/windsor.html Windsor Square – Hancock Park Historical Society] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100423114912/http://www.wshphs.org/windsor.html |date=April 23, 2010}}</ref> He owned the Rancho La Brea Oil Company and donated {{convert|23|acre|m2}} of Hancock Park to Los Angeles County in 1924 to preserve and exhibit the fossils exhumed from Rancho La Brea.<ref>http://www.tarpits.org/our-story/about-the-page</ref> The [[La Brea Tar Pits]] within the Park are a now registered [[National Natural Landmark]].
Arthur Gilmore bought some of the Rancho land in the 1890s and started a dairy farm. Drilling for water, he struck oil. This find was named the [[Salt Lake Oil Field]] after the company that drilled for him. Arthur's son Earl Gilmore built [[Gilmore Stadium]] next to [[Gilmore Field]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Healey|first=Paul|title=Gilmore Field|url=http://www.projectballpark.org/history/pcl/gilmore.html|publisher=www.projectballpark.org/|accessdate=August 28, 2010}}</ref><ref name="PMFAQ">{{cite web|title=Frequently Asked Questions|url=http://www.tarpits.org/info/faq/faqasphalt.html|publisher=Page Museum|accessdate=August 28, 2010|deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612234140/http://tarpits.org/info/faq/faqasphalt.html|archivedate=June 12, 2010|df=}}</ref>
==See also== *[[Ranchos of California]] *[[List of Ranchos of California]]
