'''Ruth Bourne''' was one of the Women of [[Bletchley Park]], recruited to help win [[World War II]] against the Germans from 1939-45. <ref>{{cite journal|url=https://academic.oup.com/itnow/article/58/2/10/1745087|title=The Women of Bletchley Park|first=Sue|last=Black|date=1 June 2016|publisher=|journal=ITNOW|volume=58|issue=2|pages=10–11|doi=10.1093/itnow/bww033}}</ref>. The Woman of Bletchley Park were a secret team put together by the government, made to sign a Secrets Act confirming that they would not tell anyone about their work there. During her time at Bletchley, Ruth Bournes' job was not only to work on the German code, but to be a bombe operator. She was one of the Wrens responsible for dismantling the bombes wire by wire after the war had ended in 1945. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/5320978.stm|title=Enigma replica 'homage to heroes'|date=6 September 2006|publisher=|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>
==Recruitment and role==
Aged 17 at the time, Ruth was a trainee Wren when she was told that she would be joining the Woman of [[Bletchley Park]]. She was offered to sign a contract that tied her into endless hours of work, no social life and no way to exit once she had agreed. Ruth was recruited to be a member of the [[HMS Pembroke]] 5 team as part of the SDX special duties<ref name="bcs.org">{{cite web|url=http://www.bcs.org/content/conWebDoc/23849|title=Video: The Women of Station X - Society - Subject areas - Publishing and editorial - BCS - The Chartered Institute for IT|website=www.bcs.org}}</ref>. [[Bletchley Park]] workers consisted of two different teams the 'y station', the woman responsible for picking up the German code and the 'x station' those who were responsible for bomb disposal, like Ruth herself.
===The job=== Majority of the woman recruited had no previous experience of bombe operation and were going in to the job blindsighted. The workers were only shown a few machines for training purposes on recruitment of the job. They were told not to ask any questions<ref name="bcs.org"/>. The role itself included "preparing the machines each day, turning the drums on the front and plugging up the boards at the back according to settings laid out in a menu"<ref name="techrepublic.com">{{cite web|url=https://www.techrepublic.com/article/the-women-who-helped-crack-nazi-codes-at-bletchley-park/|title=Hacking the Nazis: The secret story of the women who broke Hitler's codes|publisher=}}</ref>. While Ruth was a checker she would be in charge of waiting for information to come through as 'confirmed'. When this happened she would then have to make a call to report the stop on the code menu which would be checked by other members of Bletchley. <ref name="auto">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7r65N2a6wpE|title=VEDAY70 - An interview with former Turing Bombe Operator Ruth Bourne|first=|last=USEmbassyLondon|date=7 May 2015|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>. Ruths job meant that she was on her feet all day and there was little time for breaks.<ref name="techrepublic.com"/>. There was a term 'mustard' <ref name="bcs.org"/>, that meant the workers at Bletchley park were told what they was going to do without any discussion or choice of their own. From the very first day of her work as a bombe operator to when her time at Bletchley ended, Ruth did what she was told on demand <ref name="auto"/>. Despite the little amount of agency the workers had at [[Bletchley]], Bourne says herself that it was very satisfying to know that we were helping to break German codes. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2006/sep/07/secondworldwar.world|title=Back in action at Bletchley Park, the black box that broke the Enigma code|first=Esther|last=Addley|date=6 September 2006|website=the Guardian}}</ref> Her work as a bombe operator began in early 1944 and continued until the end of the war in 1945.
==After the war==
In 1945 when [[World War II]] ended, all of the workers of [[Bletchley Park]] were told that they must continue to keep their work there a secret. It wasn't until 30 years after the war (1970's) when the book "The Enigma Secret" was published that she, along with other Bletchley Park workers, were able to tell their families <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-politics-24888003/bletchley-park-they-also-served|title=Bletchley Park: they also served|website=BBC News}}</ref> about their involvement in bringing down [[Hitler]]. Ruth describes what it was like when the news finally broke saying that "you got so used to not talking to anyone"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/history/world-war-two/10619570/Can-you-keep-a-secret-The-Bletchley-codebreakers-70-years-on.html|title=Can you keep a secret? The Bletchley codebreakers 70 years on|first=Peter|last=Stanford|date=5 February 2014|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> that even after they were allowed to disclose their roles she still wouldn't talk about her experience in depth.
